A/B Testing for a promotion compaign¶

-------------- Author: Thu Nguyen ---------------------¶

Probem Descriptions:¶

Data shows the results of a experiment for a promotion campaign. The test was conducted on two groups:

  • Group A: the control group which was not subjected to the designed promotion.
  • Group B: the treatment group which was subjected to the designed promotion.
  • Each group has 1000 customers.
  • Each row contains the revenue generated by each customer before and after the compaign.

Target questions:

  1. Evaluate the revenue impact of the promotion.
  1. "Different customers may have reacted differently to the compaign". Discuss on this statement.

Remark 1¶

  • According to the scatter plot above, it is clear that Promotion has significant impact on the revenue of "group B-After Promotion", who was subjected to the promotion compaign, while there is no clear change in distribution of revenue for group A.
  • In group B (B-After Promotion), there are two groups of players who have opposite interactions to the Promotion. The customers with ID from 1000 to 2700 seem to like the Promotion, that leads to the revenue of this subgroup increases after Promotion. By contrast, the revenue of the customer group with ID from 2700 to 3000 remains unchanged, even slightly decreases.
  • For a better evaluation of the intervention's impact, I will further conduct analyses as below:

Remark 2¶

  • According to the statistic summary table and the boxplot above, we can see that the distribution of the revenue of both groups A and B before Promotion are similar. The mean, min, max, 50th percentile of group A before Promotion are 1345.16, 1316.9, 1377.4, 1345 dollars, respectively. These values of group B before Promotion are 1344.48, 1313.7, 1375.2, 1344.6 dollars, respectively.
  • After Promotion, these values of group A are nearly the same as before Promotion. However, for the group B, the mean, max increased to 1364.7, 1409.2 dollars, respectively. The values of 25th, 50th and 75th quartiles also increased significantly to 1351.2, 1369.6 and 1378.5 dollars, respectively.

Remark 3¶

From figure above, we can have following conclusions:

  1. Revenue change of Group A: Nearly Normal distribution.

    • The density curve is nearly symmetric to the vertical line at revenue = 0

    • Both left and right tails are reach to +40 and -40 dollars.

  1. Revenue change of Group B: slightly Left-Skewed distribution:

    • The density curve is not symmetric and is shifted to the right

    • The median value of the revenue change is 23.5 dollars, the mode value of revenue change is around 28 dollars.

    • The right tail reach to +80 dollars meanwhile the left tail is still -40 dollars.

    • It means that not all players within group B react the same with the intervention. Most of them react very positively to the intervention, leading to the shift of the density curve. However, there is small number of players do not react positively with the intervention, leading to the Left-Skewed distribution. This question will be investigated more carefully in the question Q2.

Hypotheses Test¶

To strenthen the conclusions above, I will further evaluate the revenue impact of the promotion by conducting Hypotheses Tests:

  • The Null Hypotheses (H0): Revenue after promotion - Revenue before promotion <= 0
  • The Alternative Hypotheses (H1): Revenue after promotion - Revenue before promotion > 0

To test the Null Hypotheses, I will simulate (bootstrap) sample data set for both groups A & B, and compute the mean value of revenue change rate for those samples:

  • Generate 10000 samples, use the sample size is 25% size of original data of each group
  • Calculate mean value of revenue change rate for those samples. Here, the revenue change rate = (Revenue change) / (Revenue before promotion)
  • Calculate p-value for null hypothesis for both group A & B
In [9]:
### first, add column "Change%" to calculate revenue change rate = (Revenue change) / (Revenue before promotion)
df_A['Change%'] = df_A['Change']/df_A['A-Before Promotion']
df_B['Change%'] = df_B['Change']/df_B['B-Before Promotion']

### second, sampling and calculate mean value of revenue change rate for those samples
Revenue_change_rates_A = []
Revenue_change_rates_B = []

for i in range(10000):
    df_A_sample = df_A.sample(frac=0.25, replace=False)
    Revenue_change_rates_A.append(df_A_sample['Change%'].mean())
    
    df_B_sample = df_B.sample(frac=0.25, replace=False)
    Revenue_change_rates_B.append(df_B_sample['Change%'].mean())
    
df_Revenue_change_rates_A = pd.DataFrame(Revenue_change_rates_A, columns=['Change%'])
df_Revenue_change_rates_B = pd.DataFrame(Revenue_change_rates_B, columns=['Change%'])

In [11]:
### Finally, plot normal distribution of null hypothesis and calculate p-value for each group
def normal_distribution_null_hypothesis(df_Revenue_change_rates_A, group_name):
    null_vals= np.random.normal(0, df_Revenue_change_rates_A['Change%'].std(), df_Revenue_change_rates_A['Change%'].size)
    plt.hist(null_vals, bins=20)
    plt.axvline(x= df_Revenue_change_rates_A['Change%'].mean(), color= 'r')
    plt.xticks(rotation=90)
    title = group_name+":Null hypothsis p-value is: {}".format((null_vals > df_Revenue_change_rates_A['Change%'].mean()).mean())
    plt.title(title)
    
    
plt.figure(figsize=(12,4))
plt.rc('font', size=11)

#### null hypothesis for group A
plt.subplot(1,2,1)
normal_distribution_null_hypothesis(df_Revenue_change_rates_A, 'Group A')
#### null hypothesis for group B
plt.subplot(1,2,2)
normal_distribution_null_hypothesis(df_Revenue_change_rates_B, 'Group B')

Remark 4¶

  • The p-value of null hypothesis for group A is 0.3181, accept null hypothesis for group A
  • The p-value of null hypothesis for group B is 0.000, reject null hypothesis for group B
  • Combining with the remarks 2 & 3 in previous section, it is clearly concluded that the promotion did have possitve impact on the revenue changes. Details of revenue changes for group B (which is subjected to the promotion) are presented in remarks 2 & 3.

Q2. Different players may have reacted differently to the intervention. Discuss on this statement.¶

  • First, by combining the remarks from the density plot of revenue change in the previous section with the below scatter plot (Fig.1), we can have a general observation that within group B, different players do react differently to the intervention. But how is difference?
  • As shown in Fig.1: Revenue Change Vs PlayerId, the customer group with ID from 2000 to 2700 seems to have more activities, that leads to the revenue of this sub group increased after promotion. By contrast, the revenue of the customer group with ID from 2700 to 3000 remains unchanged, even decreases.
  • The distribution of scatters also suggest a potential Clustering such as KMeans-Clustering to group the players into different groups. However, it is noted that the x-axis of this plot is the player ID which generally (in practice) does not have real meaning related to player's personalities. Therefore, clustering based on PlayerId will lead to some missleading intepretations.
  • On the other hand, as shown in Fig.2: Revenue Change Vs Old Revenue, we can see a potential relation that the Revenue Change decreases as the Revenue before change increase. This may suggest some regression analyses.

  • Next step, I will try to quickly build a simple linear regression model to find out a representable relation between two parameters.
In [15]:
# remove PlayerId and B_After Change since it will not be used for building model.
# The PlayerId normally is the ID and does not has real personal meaning
# The B_After cannot be kept since 'B_After' is dependent to 'B-Before Change' and 'Change'

df_B = df_B[['B-Before Promotion','Change']]

# Split train set and test set: 
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
df_train, df_test = train_test_split(df_B, test_size=0.2, random_state=42)
X_train = df_train['B-Before Promotion']
y_train = df_train['Change']

X_test = df_test['B-Before Promotion']
y_test = df_test['Change']

# Scale data using StandardScaler
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler
autoscaler = StandardScaler()
X_2Darray = X_train.values.reshape(-1,1)
X_train_scaled = autoscaler.fit_transform(X_2Darray)

### Linear regression
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression
from sklearn.model_selection import cross_val_score

lin_reg = LinearRegression()

### Use K-fold cross validation method with 5 folds
scores = cross_val_score(lin_reg, X_train_scaled, y_train,scoring="neg_mean_squared_error", cv=5)
lin_reg_rmse_scores = np.sqrt(-scores)
print(lin_reg_rmse_scores.mean())

lin_reg.fit(X_train_scaled, y_train)
print('Model coefficients: ', lin_reg.coef_)
print('Model intercept: ', lin_reg.intercept_)

  • In conclusion, majority of players in group B react quite positively with the intervention.
  • There are a small number of players who spent less when subjected to the intervention.
  • There is a contra - variant relationship between the Revenue before intervention and the Revenue change due to the intervention. It means that the intervention seems work better for the players who used to spend less. For players who used to generate good revenues, there are certain probabilities that they react negatively to the intervention or they might not react as well as the remainders.
